Access the third element of an array like this:
```
arr = array(of customers);
i = index(of 'city');
value = arr[i].City;
```

Access the attributes of an object like this:
```
car.make = 'Porsche';
car.model = '911 Turbo S';
```

Use the following syntax to call your function:
```
function name(parameters).where(condition).do{
    // Function code here
}
```
where 'name' is the name of the function, and 'parameters' are any necessary arguments for it. For example, here is how you would call a simple function that takes two integers as parameters:
```
add(a, b).where(a > b).do{
    // Adds the values of a and b together
};
```

Use one of these statements to declare a variable of the specified type:

```
declare integer age;
or
declare string name;
```

Use one of these statements to call a procedure:

```
call procedure add(a, b);
or
create procedure subtract(c, d);
```

You can create arrays with any combination of data types. Here's how to declare one:
```
car = new Object({
    make: 'Porsche',
    model: '911 Turbo S',
    year: 2021,
    color: '#FF0000',
});
```
where 'car' is the name of your new object. This example shows you how to define attributes for a car object using 4 simple statements: its make, model, year (which should be between 1903 and today), and color attribute values. You can also add more complex attributes like boolean flags or enumerations if needed. Just remember that Actian 4GL supports all major programming languages so no matter what type of data you need to store â€“ it has you covered!

Use the 'menu' object and its 'items' property to create a popup menu. For example, here is how you might create a simple menu with three items:
```
let menu = new menu();
menu.title = 'Settings';
menu.items = [
    new menuitem('Font'),
    new separator(),
    new menuitem('Size')
];
```

Remove the last row from an array like this:
```
arr = array(of inventory);
arr.DeleteRow(arr.Lastrow);
```

Insert a new record into an array like this:
```
arr = array(of customers);
new_record = record({
    Name = 'Jane Doe',
    Address = '123 Main St',
    City = 'Anytown'
});
arr.Add(new_record);
```

Use the following syntax to add elements to your array:
```
append(element) to numbers;
```
where 'element' is the value of the element being added. For example, here is how you would add three integers:
```
append(1);
append(2);
append(3);
```

Use the following code to create a function that does just that:
```
function totalCostOfCar(car) {
    let basePrice = car.price;
    let insurance = basePrice * 0.05;
    let fuel = (2 * car.mileage) * 12;
    let maintenance = (2 * car.years) * 0.1;
    return basePrice + insurance + fuel + maintenance;
}
```

